Rockland Police Chief Tim Carroll warned the community in the days after the crash that the investigation would “be very time-consuming to ensure that we get it right.”

On Thursday, the department said that the investigation included interviews with “numerous witnesses,” reviewing records and consultation with experts.

Brayden’s parents have [hired a lawyer to represent them in legal action](https://www.pressherald.com/2025/12/17/parents-of-boy-killed-in-rockland-school-bus-crash-consider-lawsuit/) against Regional School Unit 13, seeking $10 million in monetary damages. The Maine Tort Claims Act, however, caps damages at $400,000 and gives the school 120 days to respond out of court before a lawsuit can be filed in state court.

Colburn was involved in a minor crash in October in which he hit a parked car while driving an RSU 13 bus. He was also convicted of operating a vehicle under the influence of alcohol in 2015, for which he received a $500 fine and had his license suspended for 150 days.

